  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Installing Recharts for Visualization**\n\nI\'ve made progress! I\'ve confirmed that `recharts` isn\'t currently in `package.json`. Therefore, I\'m now going to install it. The objective is to create compelling visualizations that can present the therapist\'s workload and to show the distribution of assigned slots and optimization metrics using these charts. I am confident this installation will make significant improvements.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Custom SVG Charts**\n\nI\'ve shifted focus. After considering options, I\'m now leaning towards building custom, interactive SVG charts using Tailwind and `motion`. This approach offers beautiful animation, avoids potential React 19 compatibility issues that can arise with `recharts`, and allows for pixel-perfect design. I\'m confident this custom route will result in a more robust, performant, and visually stunning dashboard.\n\n\n**Defining Time Slots & Slots**\n\nI\'m now determining the schedule\'s structure, working to calculate the number of 20-minute slots in a standard workday (9:00 to 17:00), which results in 24 slots. I\'ve created the detailed list of time slot breakdowns for clarity and visualization. This information is key for scheduling optimization metrics later.\n\n\n**Enumerating Constraints & Elements**\n\nI\'m now cataloging all constraints and available elements. I\'ve broken down: therapist and patient attributes, required daily slots per patient type, and NG therapist lists. I\'ve documented the mandatory therapist breaks (60 mins), the double-booking restrictions, and constraints such as avoiding patient assignments to their NG list. I am working through a few additional elements.\n\n\n**Defining Patient Constraints**\n\nI\'m now focusing on satisfying orders, assigning therapist attributes and slot counts per patient, and have established soft constraints. This includes separating multiple patient sessions by at least 40 minutes (2 empty slots). I\'m translating this timing requirement into slot indices. The objective is to minimize the variance in the number of assigned slots across therapists to ensure even distribution and workload balance.\n\n\n**Designing the Scheduler Engine**\n\nI\'m now devising the core architecture. I\'m focusing on crafting a highly optimized scheduling algorithm in TypeScript for the browser, aiming for speed and reliability, and ensuring a valid solution within seconds. I\'m excited about the modular design to prevent token limit issues, as I am defining key files and their responsibilities: data structures in `types.ts`, a realistic dataset in `initialData.ts`, the solver in `scheduler.ts`, dashboard elements in `Dashboard.tsx`, and a visual schedule grid in `ScheduleGrid.tsx`.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will update `metadata.json` to provide a descriptive name and description in Japanese for the rehabilitation scheduling application."
