  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing the Data Needs**\n\nOkay, I\'m now focusing on how to enable checking and modifying patient orders and restricted therapist information in a table format. I\'m visualizing the data structure and potential user interactions. The goal is to provide a clear and intuitive interface for healthcare professionals.\n\n\n**Designing the Table Interface**\n\nOkay, I\'m now implementing the table view in `PatientList.tsx`. The design will feature a Tailwind-styled table with specific headings for patient data. I\'m focusing on making patient names and orders editable inline using input elements, deciding between immediate updates on change or updates on blur. I\'m leaning towards a debounced update on change for efficiency and to avoid constant state refreshes, now considering both `onUpdatePatient` and local state solutions.\n\n\n**Implementing Direct Updates**\n\nI\'ve realized that direct updates in React input elements are straightforward and fast using `onChange`. The code is concise and works perfectly, updating inline patient names immediately. The increment/decrement buttons for therapy orders will be in a similar structure, providing immediate feedback. I like that so far.\n\n\n**Refining the Therapist View**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the therapist selection interface. The increment/decrement buttons are working well, and now I\'m thinking about the therapists. I\'m imagining a workflow where they can add or remove therapists directly from the table, maybe with small tags showing the therapists and a button/dropdown nearby. I think a simple native `<select>` dropdown next to the tags with a default option to add therapists is the most elegant solution.\n\n\n**Perfecting the Therapist Selector**\n\nI\'ve just landed on an *extremely* simple and elegant therapist selection design. When a therapist is selected from the dropdown, I append their ID to the `ngTherapistIds` array and then reset the dropdown, avoiding any need for popovers or floating window logic. The code is concise and removes therapists just as simply. The inline display, with an \"x\" to remove them, is clear.\n\n\n**Evaluating the UI Design**\n\nOkay, the interface feels complete and elegant now. The inline display with the \"x\" to remove therapists is clear, and adding therapists via the dropdown is seamless. I\'m pleased with how efficient and intuitive the design is. It\'s concise, avoiding complex positioning or click-away listeners.\n\n\n**Adding Table Search**\n\nI\'m now integrating a search filter for patient names or IDs directly into the table view. Since I already have a `filtered` patient array, implementing this should be straightforward. I\'ll focus on adding a search input and dynamically updating the displayed data based on the search query. This will enhance the overall usability and make finding specific patients much easier.\n\n\n**Adding View Controls**\n\nI\'m now thinking about adding view toggle controls. I\'m imagining a control to switch between a table and a card view, perhaps implemented as a simple toggle selector. This would enhance the flexibility of the patient list display. I\'m evaluating the best placement for it, either next to the \"\346\202\243\350\200\205\343\202\222\350\277\275\345\212\240\" button or within the existing filters header.\n\n\n**Implementing View Controls**\n\nI\'ve just added a view toggle to switch between table and card display modes. The buttons provide clear visual feedback, enhancing the user experience. The table view layout and interactivity is working, and feels great so far. I\'m focusing on the integration and design of this control and layout.\n\n\n\n**Refining the Table Layout**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the table\'s structure for clarity and readability. I\'m reviewing the column headings for each data point: Patient ID, Patient Name, PT, OT, ST, Restricted Therapists (NG\346\203\205\345\240\261), and Actions, ensuring each row is well-organized. I\'m focusing on text alignment and column widths for the best visual presentation of the data.\n\n\n**Refining the UI Components**\n\nI\'m now polishing the input field design in the table. I\'m focusing on ensuring consistent styling and functionality. I have the Patient ID displayed with bold, subtle gray text, while the input for patient name is a clean, visually distinct field. The PT, OT, and ST order buttons are also implemented in a similar style, with clear, direct actions. I\'m working to make the UI as clean and user-friendly as possible.\n\n\n**Improving Order Interface**\n\nI\'m now focusing on optimizing the direct update buttons for therapy orders. I\'m reviewing the current UI implementation, where I have \"+\" and \"-\" buttons next to the order counts. I\'m focusing on ensuring responsiveness, and evaluating the design for visual clarity and ease of use. I\'m aiming for a straightforward and efficient user experience for incrementing and decrementing therapy orders.\n\n\n**Optimizing Order Updates**\n\nI\'m now implementing the order update logic, starting with negative order value handling and adjusting the minimums to zero. I\'m ensuring all the therapy order buttons are fully responsive and visually clear. The design is becoming streamlined, which is what I wanted.\n\n\n**Refining the UI Controls**\n\nI\'m now integrating the order controls with their corresponding updates. I\'m focusing on ensuring responsiveness for all three therapy types: PT, OT, and ST. The button styles are consistent, the UI feels good, and I\'m very happy with how efficient the design is now.\n\n\n**Evaluating Button Styling**\n\nI\'m now polishing the visual design of the order increment/decrement buttons for consistency. I\'m focusing on ensuring the styling is clear and consistent across all three therapy types: PT, OT, and ST. The button styles are consistent with other table elements, and are now fully functional. I\'m aiming for an integrated and polished user experience.\n\n\n**Refining the Therapist View**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the visual presentation of therapists within the patient table. The existing design for therapist selection and removal works well. I\'m focusing on ensuring consistency and clarity, evaluating the style and placement of the therapists within the patient table. I\'m aiming for a straightforward and elegant solution that integrates seamlessly with the existing UI.\n\n\n**Improving Therapist Interface**\n\nI\'m now focusing on further refining the therapist selection logic in the patient table. I\'m focusing on ensuring responsiveness for therapist additions. The dropdown now includes disabled options for therapists already assigned to the patient, ensuring there are no duplicates. The addition function works well and is elegant.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing the UI Layout**\n\nI\'m now implementing the patient removal function and related visual feedback within the table. I\'m focusing on ensuring the delete function works as intended and on making the button look good. I\'m aiming for a straightforward and efficient user experience for removing patients.\n\n\n\n"
